grad_female_final_graph <- ggplot(grad_enroll, aes(x = Year, y = Total_Females)) +

Figure 1. Total Female Enrollment in Graduate Programs (1967-2015). Annual enrollment by women in graduate programs between 1967 and 2015. Year significantly predicts graduate enrollment (b = 30126, t(47) = 51.66, p < 0.001) with a strong positive correlation (Pearsons r = 0.99). The overall model signficantly explains womens enrollment each year (F(1,47) = 2669, p < 0.001, R2 = 0.98). Gray border indicates the 95% confidence interval for the mean predicted value.

Figure 2. Total Male Enrollment in Graduate Programs (1967-2015). Annual enrollment by men in graduate programs between 1967 and 2015. Year significantly predicts graduate enrollment (b = 9069, t(47) = 16.61, p < 0.001) with a strong positive correlation (Pearsons r = 0.99). The overall model signficantly explains womens enrollment each year (F(1,47) = 276, p < 0.001, R2 = 0.85). Gray border indicates the 95% confidence interval for the mean predicted value.
